FOR ADVANCED CLASSES, AND FOR SELFTRAINING IN READING.
Elocution, or the art of reading and speaking, may
be divided into Vocal Culture and Expression.
An exhaustive analysis of the subject is not attempted
in the following pages. Nor does the student need this;
he only needs a few practical directions to aid him in
getting the mastery over his voice, and in acquiring a distinct conception of the various styles of composition. By
the aid of appropriate examples under each division, and
abundant miscellaneous reading exercises, at the close of
the book, it is hoped the directions will be found sufficient for this purpose.
To the class, no book can supply the place of the living
teacher. To the student, nothing can make up for a want
of judgment and taste: without these, he can not hope to
become an elegant reader; with them, by attention to vocal
culture, he will experience but little difficulty.  Strength
and smoothness of tone are too frequently regarded as the
gift of nature. True, nature may favor many in this respect; but any one whose organs of speech are not defective may, by proper exercise and attention, acquire a deep,
full, clear, resonant voice.
Breathing.-Much of the success in reading depends
upon breathing. No one can read well who can not breathe
well. The first exercise, therefore, in a course of vocal
training, should be one in breathing.
(111)INST'ITUTE READER
Stand or sit erect (standing is preferable), place the
hands upon the waist, the fingers forward, and the shoulders thrown well back. Breathe naturally but deeply; increase in rapidity until you can instantly inflate and as
suddenly exhaust the lungs. In breathing, let there be a
free action of the diaphragm and abdominal muscles, and
let the chest rise and fall freely, but do not allow even the
slightest noise to be made. A good practice is to inhale
deeply and give out the breath slowly in one of the prolonged vowel sounds.
Emphasis and Inflection.-Emphasis is calling atten.
tion to a particular word of a sentence, by some modulation
of the utterance; inflection, the agreeable and forcible enunciation of each word. These need but little, if any, special
notice. A correct idea of the writer's meaning will suggest
the proper emphasis and inflection; a well-trained voice will
enable the reader to give them accurately.
Suggestion.-To make the use of this part serviceable,
the student should first go through with a thorough course in
articulation and breathing; then take up Vocal Culture,
beginning with Quality, and drill on each division and
subdivision, reviewing, from time to time, as he advances,
until complete control over the voice is secured.  He
should next proceed to expression, and obtain an idea of
the various kinds of style.
