SECTION IV.- PITCH.
Pitch is the point on the musical scale where the element
or word is sounded. It must not be mistaken for compass,
nor confounded with loudness or Quantity. While Quantity is frequently associated with Pitch, it is by no means
essential to it.
The ability to manage the voice, with reference to Pitch,
depends upon the control of the larynx and lower jaw. If
the muscles be relaxed and the throat enlarged, the Pitch
will be low; and each degree of contraction will be marked
by a higher degree of Pitch.
The best means of cultivating this, is to speak to persons
at different distances-far or near, according as a high or
low degree is desired. Exercise in sudden transitions in
Pitch will also be found invaluable to a complete mastery
of the subject.
The distinctions of Pitch are-Low, Very Low, Middle,
High, Very High.
