THE ability to use the voice at pleasure, in all the varie
ties of Quality, Force, Stress, Pitch, Quantity, and NMovement having been obtained, the next subject that should
engage the attention of the student of elocution, is Expressionz. While this implies a knowledge of Vocal Culture, it
comprehends much more. It is the life, the soul of read.
ing or speaking.
Although no invariable rules can be given for the cultivation of this faculty, a few suggestions may be of great advantage to the student:
(I) Study the author you read, and endeavor to make his
spirit, as revealed in the composition, your own; and then,
by appropriate Quality, Force, Stress, Pitch, Quantity, and
Movement, give expression to it.
(2j Suit the tones of the voice to the style of the composition. Do not read simple narrative as you would an
impassioned oration. If you are not able to distinguish the
difference in composition and feeling between the unadorned
narrative and the ornate sublime, or invective dramatic, it
will be impossible for you to read these styles withl good
effect. The ability to read impressively, implies a knowledge of the fundamental principles of rhetoric, so far, at
least, as they apply to style.
(3) Attend to the expression of the thought, not.to the
sound of the words. If your mind is fixed on the modulation rather than on the meaning, you will impress your
hearers with the idea that you are acting for their anmusement, and not reading for their instruction. The shortest
road to the expression is through the meaning. There is a
Droper time for attending to the delivery, the tones of
voice, modulation, emphasis, etc.; but it is before the
reader confronts his audience.
