(4) Never impress your hearers with the thought of the
fine drill you have passed through. To avoid this, you
must not practice less, but more: make your preparation a
second nature.
(5) Be natural; but do not confound the natural with
the familiar; they are widely different in character and
effect. Every one loves to be naturally, but few familiarly,
spoken to; and he offends his audience who attempts to
be familiar with them.
