VI.-Scriptural Style.     I'
The style of composition in which the Bible has come
down to us, being the old English, into which it was
originally translated, is somewhat peculiar; for this reason,
together with the sacredness belonging to the Scriptures,
and the fact of their being so universally read by all classes,
some prominence should be given to it.
While there are no rules which have any exclusive application to the reading of the Sacred Writings, there are,
however, two prevalent methods of reading them, both of
which should be carefully avoided.  One may be termed
the sanctiononious, and the other, the careless method. Let
the reader remember their high authority, and that what
he reads has a personal application to himself, and to each
of his hearers, and then observe the same rules he would
were he reading from a profane writer.
