The blackboard is preferable, for some reasons, to charts
and dissected cards, which are now in use in many schools.
Children regard those things with greater interest in which
they feel a degree of ownership; and they are more intimately connected withl what they have, at least, caused to
be made, and have seen executed, than in what is hung up
before them, from day to day, already printed. Then, too,
there is a freshness about printing on the blackboard, which
cards and charts do not possess.
If you can secure the charts and cards, however, use
them; but not to the exclusion of the blackboard.
