XIII.-MY OLD HOME.
How vividly the picture rises before my mind as I write:
the quaint old house, with its many projections and odd
nooks-its inconvenient stairs and queer little lean-to, the
scene of so many boyish experiments in carpentering, painting, and the like!
And then its grand old attic, which, to our childish fancy,
seemed an inexhaustible store-house of treasure, that we
dragged forth from gloomy corners in shuddering haste,
almost feeling a ghostly hand upon our shoulders, or seeing
the gleam of a pair of ghostly eyes!
What a bright, cheerful, happy home it was! How the
sun streamed into the "keeping-room," where the dear
mother sat, the children played, and the lazy cat stretched
first one furry side and then the other to the fire!
What glorious times we had on rainy Saturdays, sonstructing dioramnas and cutting endless menageries out of
paper, which we painted after life, and exhibited for a
penny a head! How our quiet mother, sitting sewing, her
gray hair smoothed from off her placid brow, under a muslin
cap, would praise our skill and stroke the tangled locks
from our eager faces, while the toddling little sister would
seize the opportunity to clutch some much-coveted, gaylypainted animal, and crush it in her tiny hands!
But who could be angry with the happy baby, cooing and
talking to herself over the mangled fragments? Now that
the little restless feet have long been laid to rest, the dainty
fingers meekly clasped above the pure heart, we thank thee,
Heaven, that no reproachful word or angry deed comes back
to us, to turn our quiet sorrow into stinging remorse!
How swiftly the afternoon flew by, as we sat by the
