FROM   THE DESERTED        VILLAGE.
OLIVER GOLDSMITH.
OLIVER GOLDSMITH was born at Pallas, Ireland, November, 1728.
At college, he was not noted for his close application to books; but
was given to rambling and dissipation. After leaving college, he
traveled on foot through Flanders, France, and Switzerland, with
no means of procuring a subsistence save his skill in disputation
and in playing the flute.
On returning to England, in 1756, he began his literary career as
a newspaper writer, in London; and died at the age of forty-six.
His writings, both in prose and poetry, are characterized by a
clear. pure, and classic style. The most noted of his writings are,
"The Traveler", "The Deserted Village", "The Vicar of Wakefield", and "Animated Nature."
XXII.-THE VILLAGE PREACHER.
NEAR yonder copse, where once the garden smiled,
And still where many a garden flower grows wild,
There, where a few torn shrubs the place disclose,
The village preacher's modest mansion rose.
A man he was to all the country dear,
And passing rich with forty pounds a year.
Remote from towns he ran his godly race,
Nor e'er had changed, nor wished to change his place;
Unskillful he to fawn, or seek for power,
By doctrines fashioned to the varying hour;
Far other aims his heart had learned to prize,
More bent to raise the wretched than to rise.
