Inflection.--It would be folly to attempt to give specific directions for the inflection of each word of a sentence.
This general rule, however, may safely be adopted: Let the
inflection of principal words be well marked, so that it will
be readily known whether the rising or falling inflection is
intended. If you have difficulty in getting your pupils to
inflect their words properly, the plan recommended for
securing interest-that of substituting different words-will
be found to be an excellent auxiliary. Another plan, perhaps the best one, is the following: After the sentence has
been read so frequently as to be remembered, have the pupil
repeat it without looking on the book, and the voice will
naturally take the proper inflection. Ask the pupil to say it
to you just as he would talk it, or direct him to say it to
the class.
Let declarative sentences be read with the downward
inflection, and be particularly careful of the last word of
each sentence. The child will very probably make the fill
stop by running the last three or four words lower and lower,
the last one being scarcely audible. Instead of this, the
force should be kept up to the close, and the last word
uttered with greater force than the ones immediately preceding.
All direct interrogative sentences should be read with the
ulpward inflection. In exclamatory sentences, let nature be
strictly followed, with this comprehensive rule: Give full
sway to your surprise, and assist the voice by dropping the
chin and opening the eyes a little.
