WASHINGTON IRVING.
IN rural life, there is nothing mean and debasing. It
leads a man forth among scenes of natural grandeur and
beauty; it leaves him to the workings of his mind, operated
upon by the purest and most elevating of external influences. Such a man may be simple and rough, but he can
not be vulgar. The man of refinement, therefore, finds
nothing revolting in an intercourse with the lower orders
in rural life, as he does when he casually mingles with the,ower orders of cities. He lays aside his distance and reserve, and is glad to waive the distinctions of rank, and to
enter into the honest, heartfelt enjoyments of common life.
