but it would be suicidal to take the first session to such a
place.
Invitations from various towns may be received and considered before selecting the place.
Entertainment of Teachers.-A committee resident
in the place of holding the Institute should be appointed to
attend to this matter. If the session is not longer than one
week, the ladies, at least, may be entertained free of charge;
or if not, then at reduced rates, and the gentlemen at nominal prices. This committee should canvass the town and
vicinity, and secure a list of the names of the families that
will receive teachers, also, how many and at what prices,
that they may be able, when the teachers assemble on the
morning and in the room   advertised, to assign them  to
places without confusion or delay.
How   long held.-This must be determined by the
wants of the county, the funds at the disposal of the manigers, and the interest manifested by the teachers. If it be
347INSTITUTE READER.
necessary to furnish regular instruction in the text-books,
then the Institute assumes an academical character, and the
session may be continued, with profit, from four to six
weeks. During the term, lessons should be assigned, studied,
and recited as in any other school, with additional instruction in methods of teaching. But the legitimate work of
the Institute proper is to give shape and direction to the
knowledge already acquired; to impart instruction in new
and improved methods of teaching and government; to
quicken thought; to awaken professional spirit; and to cultivate a unity of interest among teachers. To these ends, a
session of one or two weeks, conducted by experienced instructors, will accomplish more than one inefficiently conducted for a much longer time.
Who should attend.-All active teachers will avail
themselves of this means of advancing their profession and
the cause of education; young teachers should not allow the
opportunity afforded them of securing the great advantage
to be derived from  the experience of old and successful
teachers to pass unimproved; those who contemplate teaching in the future should secure to themselves the information
thus offered on school management and discipline. These
persons should make it their special business to attend; and
school officers, parents, and all friends of education should
lend the enterprise the encoiuragement of their presence.
Expenses, how defrayed.-In some States, approyri
ations are made by law for paying the expenses of instruction
in Institutes. The County Auditor will furnish a copy of the
school law containing the statutes upon the subject, and the
steps necessary to be taken in order to secure the funds. If
there be no appropriation, or if it be inadequate, it will be
necessary for those calling the Institute to assume the
responsibility of meeting the expenses. There are various
ways by which the managers may insure themselves against
loss. They may secure, beforehand, the names of a sufficient
number of teachers, with pledges to attend and assist, or
they mlay announce the tuition fee with the call for the In348TEACHERS' INSTITUTES.
stitute, and rely on the attendance being sufficiently large
to defray the expenses.
After an organization is effected, a membership fee, to be
paid annually and in advance, if thought best, may be fixed,
or it may be resolved to meet all outlays by an equal taxaation of the members. In some places, they may be met in
part by the proceeds from concerts, lectures, readings, etc.,
or by donations from citizens.
Instructors.-There should be at least one practical
teacher who has had experience in conducting Institutes.
To secure the services of such a person, it may be required
to pay what, at first thought, may seem to be a high price.
But such an expenditure, if judiciously made, will result in
profit; for teachers will be more completely satisfied, and
will be better prepared for their labors in the school-room,
than if an incompetent instructor be employed.
It is not meant that one person should do all the teaching;
but that he should give direction to the whole, and have special
charge of the department of Theory and Practice of Teaching. The exercises in reading, arithmetic, geography, writing, and spelling may be conducted by teachers of the
county who have been successful in teaching particular
branches, and who have standing in the profession. These
should be remunerated, but, because they are residents of
the county, and have their interests identified therewith, a
less compensation would be just.
The practice of employing persons to lecture upon subjects
that do not come directly within the range of the profession,
exhausts the funds without furnishing practical information.
If, however, such lectures can be made to pay their own expenses, they will add to the interest of the session, ond will
give the Institute character among the citizens.  Let tnem
form  evening' entertainments, as much for the benefit of
citizens as of teachers, but never let them take the place of
regular Institute training.  In every county, there is local
talent which may be employed in this direction. There are
ministers, lawyers, doctors, and other persons of culture who
will cheerfully contribute lectures upon moral education,
34SINSTII'UTE hEADER.
school law, physiology, and literature, if they are solicited
to do so some time before the meeting of the Institute.
The first day.-The success of an Institute depends, to
a great degree, upon the impression made at the commencement. A plan, therefore, should be fully matured, that
nothing may be left to the emergency of the hour. The
managers should meet the teachers with a friendly greeting,
and see that strangers are introduced to each other.  To
assist in this, a committee, consisting of a few teachers, well
acquainted in the county, may be appointed.
If thought desirable, a short session may be held during
the forenoon to inaugurate the regular order of exercises, or
an address of welcome may be made, closing with an announcement of the programme for the afternoon.
Temporary organization.-If the enterprise is a private one, the projector, of course, is manager; but if it be
an association of teachers, it will be necessary to effect a
temporary organization the first day, by electing the proper
officers and committees.
Permanent organization.-Some time during the first
session, perhaps on the last day, a permanent organization
should be made. A day or two previous to its close a committee may be appointed to prepare and report a constitution. The constitution should be as brief as possible.  Half
a dozen short articles will contain all that is necessary to be
specified.  It should provide for the election of a president,
a secretary, a treasurer, and an executive committee of three
members, the president and secretary being made, ex officio,
members of the committee. To this committee, should be
intrusted the entire management of the Institute.  If there
are no funds provided for by statute, or if they are inadequate, an article establishing a tuition or membership fee
may be introduced. The constitution being adopted. the
election of officers will complete the organization
