SECTION II.- SUGGESTIONS.
The Plan.-The Order of Exercises just laid down, and
the instructions which follow, are based on the model of a
well regulated and well taught school. As the best way of
presenting a method of teaching is by illustration, it is contemplated that each branch shall first be illustrated by a
recitation, and then discussed. But little time is needed for
the presentation of well matured methods, and none others
should be presented.
Classes.-An instructor may lecture to an Institute
numbering a hundred or more, but the effort to conduct a
recitation with a class of that number will prove unsatisfactory.  Where a division into classes is thought best, the following plan is recommended: On the first day of the session
the secretary should organize the teachers into classes, each
class not to exceed twenty in number, and assign those
coming in afterward to one of the classes already formed.
Every recitation should be conducted in the presence of all
the teachers, and those not reciting should constitute a committee of observation.  When the recitation is concluded
they should offer such criticisms, or make such inquiries as
may be proper and beneficial. That all may have the benefit
of an exercise in each branch of study, the classes should
alternate-the class in Orthography one day being thle
Reading class of the next, etc.
352TEA CIHERS' I7NSTITlUTES.
Branches of Study Taught.-In most of the states,
Orthography, Reading, Writing, Arithmetic, English Grammar, Geography, and the Theory and Practice of Teachinig
are called " legal branches," because the law requires that
teachers shall be familiar with them before receiving certificates of qualification to teach. While in most countics,
therefore, the principal part of the instruction should be
(levoted to these subjects, others may be brought in incidentally, and much useful knowledge may be imparted.
Orthography.-The aim of the instruction in this should
be, (i.) To secure the clear and forcible enunciation of letters and words; (2.) Phonetic spelling and analysis of words;
(3.) Methods of teaching the alphabet; (4.) Oral spelling;
(5.) Written spelling; (6.) Methods of conducting spelling
mlatches; (7.) Spelling and defining; (8.) Spelling from reading lessons and from dictionaries; (9.) Spelling geographical
and proper names; (io.) Spelling names of things belonging
to the different trades and occupations; (II.) Names of
natural objects, etc.; all of which should be illustrated.
Reading.--A very common error on this subject is that
of substituting elocutionary display for practical instruction.
WVhat teachers need is not a lecture on the sub&gt;,ct of elocution, but illustrations of how to teach reading by correcting
individual habits of incorrect pronunciation, ilflection, emphasis, etc.
The course of instruction should embrace, (i.) Exercises
in reading from Primer, First, Second, Third, Fourth, and
Fifth Readers; (2.) Reading with special attention to Articulation, Emphasis, and Inflection; (3.) Reading with special
attention to Quality, Force, Stress, Pitch, Quantity, and
Movement; (4.) Reading in Narrative and Descriptive styles;
(5.) Reading in Didactic and Senatorial styles; (6.) Reading
in Dramatic style; (7.) Declamations.  Practice as well as
instruction slLould be given in vocal culture, for no one can
teach reading properly, who can not himself read well. The
various methods for securing attention, awakening and maintaining interest, should also be illustraLed and discussed.
I. R. 30.
3  INTS'T1T'UTE READER.
Writing.-Upon this subject, (I.) The position of tHe
body, and the manner of holding the pen while writing;
(2.) Principles, and length of letters; (3.) Angles, curves,
and shapes; (4.) Analysis of small letters; (5.) Analysis of
capital letters; (6.) Composition, and other written exercises
as a means of teaching writing, should demand attention.
If the furniture of the room will admit of it, practical
exercises should be given; but if it will not, then the blackboard should be freely used in illustration.
In methods of teaching, the following subjects should be
considered: At what age should pupils begin to write?
Should the first lessons be with slate and pencil, or with pen
and paper? Should all the pupils in the room be required
to write at the same time?  To what extent should copies
be used? Should pupils be required to furnish books with
copies? How can the teacher best conduct the exercise?
Arithmetic.-Since teachers are usually more deficient
in arithmetical principles and methods of teaching than in
the solution of problems, most of the time allotted to this,subject should be devoted to these points, the solution of
problems being used, mainly, for illustrating the operations
and methods. The close connection between mental and
written arithmetic should not be lost sight of, but they
should be taught simultaneously, many of the problems in
written arithmetic being solved mentally.
The following topics will be found appropriate for consideration: (I.) The Fundamental Rules; (2.) Notation and
Numeration; (3.) Greatest Common Divisor and Least
Common Multiple; (4.) Common Fractions; (5.) Decimal
Fractions; (6.) Ratio and Proportion; (7.) Percentage and
Interest; (8.) Discount and Banking; (9.) Square and Cube
Roots.
Under the head of Theory and Practice as applied to arithmetic, the relative time it should occupy in the schools, is
an inquiry Iproper to be made; and the following question
might be discussed with advantage to many schools: How
can an adequate knowledge of Arithmetic be attained in less
time than is now devoted to the subject?
354TEA CHERS' INSTITUTES.
English Grammar.-Instruction in this branch should
commence with methods of teaching children the correct
use of language, by forming sentences, correcting errors in
grammar, etc. The analysis as well as the synthesis of sentences should be attended to. Special attention should be
given to the lmanzier of analysis and parsing, that the common fault of analyzing and parsing by rote may be avoided.
The tones of the voice, and the emphasis and inflection of
the words, should always indicate that the pupil understands
what he is saying. He should frequently be arrested in
the ordinary routine by calling his attention to the reaso;z.
Throughout the course, daily exercises should be given in
analysis and parsing.
The following division of the subject is given suggesting
a course of instruction in this branch: (i.) False Syntax and
Synthesis; (2.) The Parts of Speech; (3.) The Elements of
a Sentence--Principal and Subordinate; Siml)le, Complex,
and Compound; Adjective, Objective, and Adverbial; (4.)
The complex Sentence, Subordinate Clauses; (5.) The Compound Sentence, Co-ordinate Clauses.
Punctuation and the correct use of capitals in writing
should not be neglected. The aim in all grammatical instruction should be to make prac/ical grammarians. To this
end, composition exercises wvill be found an invaluable
assistant.
Geography.-For the time devoted to it, the results
secured in Geography are, perhaps, more unsatisfactory than
in any other branch.  Methods of teaching it should, therefore, be made very prominent, and the lessons in it should
be given, as far as practicable, as models in teaching. The
way of presenting facts to be remembered, should be explained, and the law of association, in its application to
this subject, should be fully developed and illustrated. The
outline of the continents will give the direction of the
mountains, and the mountain chains and systems, in turn,
will furnish the key to the river systems.
Correct ideas of the location of places, and their direction
and distance from each other; correct impressions of the
