Theory and Practice of Teaching.-The treatment
of each branch of study should be essentially the theory and
practice of teaching it. There are some subjects demanding
attention, however, that do not belong to any branch of
study; (for a list of which see Section III.) The consideration of these should be practical.  Generalities may do well
enough for the experienced teacher, for he is supposed to be
able to work out a method of his own, but they can be of
but little service to the young teachers; this class need specific directions.
Discussions.-Should these form a part of the exercise
in theory and practice of teaching, they should not be conducted for the purpose of gainizg the question, but for the
simple purpose of eliciting the truth. The executive committee should appoint one or two persons, the day previous,
to open the discussion and give an outline of the subject
clearly and concisely stated; then let those follow who may
have something valuable to offer in the way of experienc2
or otherwise.  Those who are diffident or unaccustomed
to public speaking can present their thoughts in the form of
essays.
356TEACHERS' INSTITUTES.
Lectures.-Many of these will be given by the principal
instructor.  Others may be presented by teachers appointed
by the executive committee some time before the meeting
of the Institute. These lectures should be practical, and
should contain, if possible, something new, stated in clear
and concise language. When practicable, the points treated
of should be placed upon the blackboard in the form of an
abstract, that the teachers may copy them into their note
books for future reference and consideration.
Criticisms.-At the commencement of each day of the
session the president should appoint one or more teachers
to act as critics.
It frequently happens that criticisms are confined to mere
verbal errors or slight mistakes in syntax. These should
receive attention, but to throw the whole force of the criticisms upon them not only indicates a narrow view of the
office of the critic, but is likely to produce any thing but a
pleasant feeling in the Institute. The range of criticism
should take in the thought as well as the expression of the
speaker, and if the critic be qualified he will add materially
to the interest of the daily exercises. At the close of the day'
he may put upon the blackboard a synopsis of the exercises
which should be copied by the teachers into their note books.
Query Box.-This is a box similar to those used in balloting, placed upon the secretary's table, in which teachers
deposit such questions as they may wish to ask in this way,
legibly written on slips of paper. It may be opened at the
close of each day by the secretary, who will read the
questions, and assign them  to proper persons to be answered. The answer may be given at the time, or reserved
until the following day. These questions may take a wide
range, but it is perhaps best to confine them to practical
subjects.
The secretary should suppress any that may be asked in a
spirit of captiousness, or may be otherwise improper.
Assistant Instructors.-These have been referred to
in Chapter I. Two or three will, perhaps, be a sufficient'
357INSTITUTE READER.
number. They should have charge of the classes, and
conduct the exercises under the direction of the principal
instructor. They should keep a register of the attendance
and punctuality, and a record of each recitation, illustrating
methods of marking, etc., which can be made serviceable to
boards of examiners in determining the qualification of applicants for certificates.
Text-Books.-It will, perhaps, be impossible to secure
uniform text-books in a County Institute; but each teacher
should take with him such books as he may have been using
in the school-room. These will be useful for reference and
for preparing the daily exercises; and those who do not teach
all the year, will find this an excellent opportunity for reviewing, preparatory to beginning the next term. Besides, a comparison of authorities will be of advantage, and a knowledge
of various authors may lead to an improvement in the books
used in the different localities.
Note Books.--Every teacher should provide himself
with a small blank book, in which to make notes on the
topics discussed and the class exercises.
The advantages of this practice can not be overestimated.
Many valuable suggestions are made which seem plain and
=easy to be remembered at the time, but which are soon
crowded out of the mind by something else, and forgotten.
If a note be made of them, they can be recalled as they are
needed' in the school-room.
-n addition to the notes of each exercise, the synopsis of
the'- day's work as put upon the blackboard by the critic
should be copied.
Evening Exercises.-During the session, two or three
evenings of each week may be devoted to lectures, conference meetings, etc. The exercises need not be so exclusively professional as those of the day, and a general invitation to aftend them should be extended to the citizens.
The discussion of the educational movements of the age,
lectures upon scho9l law, moral education, and various other
topics, are not only proper but highly profitable. Very
358TEACHERS' INSTITUTES.
pleasant entertainments, consisting of essays, declamations,
and select readings, interspersed with appropriate music,
may be given by the teachers themselves.
Social Reunions.-Sociability is a quality which should
be cultivated during the entire session. An Institiute from
which teachers go away without knowing one another better
than when they first met, has failed in a very important
particular. An evening of the session may be devoted to a
social reunion. On such an occasion it is customary to have
refreshments of some kind, toasts, responses, etc.; but the
main object should be social enjoyment.
The President.-The duties of this officer are so important that a notice of them is deemed in place. Upon
him, in connection with the executive committee, depends
almost entirely the success of the Institute. It is sometimes
the practice to elect an honorary president. This should
never be done. He should be selected for his capacity and
fitness for the office alone, and should be present at every
exercise of the Institute.
It is not necessary, though desirable, that he should be
an active teacher. He should possess tact in management,
that he may bring out the talent of all the teachers at the
proper time; especially will he have need of this faculty in
conducting that part of the exercise in theory and practice
of teaching committed to the teachers. He should be afiable and courteous, but inflexible in his adherence to the timle
allotted to each exercise, in no instance allowing one subject
to trespass upon the time of another, but announllcing each
at the minute appointed.
