TO THE TEACHER OF THIRD, FOURTH, AND
FIFTH READERS.
THE reason for this division into parfs is not so much orn
account of the difference in the application of the Rules and
Directions to the various grades, as on account of the difference in the mattcr appropriate for reading exercises.
Many of the Rules laid down in Part I will be found to
be specially applicable to Third, Fourth, and Fifth Readers,
and should be carefully studied by the teacher of those
books.
The Teacher's Preparation.- However long you
may have taught reading, or however well you read, you will
find it greatly to your advantage-absolutely necessary to a
high degree of success in teaching-to study each lesson
before hearing it recited. By this course you will qualify
yourself the better to direct the proper emphasis, inflection,
and general expression; to detect any double or delicate
shade of meaning; and, what is of vital importance, you will
thereby increase your own interest in the lesson. No lesson
should be thought so simple and easy as not to need this
attention. Even the Primer and First Reader will be far
better taught from such previous study.
Study the Book you Teach.-Many teachers fail because they are not in sympathy with the book they use. Do
not follow any book slavishly; but if you neglect to study
the plan of your author until you catch his spirit and make
it your own, you had better change your text. If you
(63)INSTITUTE READER
possess no confidence yourself, you can inspire none in
your pupils.  The book may contain errors; if so, point
them out cautiously, but make no attack upon your author,
lest your pupils take the liberty of attacking your positions
and declarations.
Articulation.-This will require careful, constant, un
wearied attention.  In any good Third, Fourth, or Fifth
Reader will be found special exercises on this subject, which
ought, on no account, to be neglected. Remember they are
intended for dr'll exercises, and, therefore, be not satisfied
with pronouncing them once or twice, as though they were
merely to be read over, but take them up, one by one, and
repeat a dozen times, or until all in the class,an give them
correctly.  Attend to it, that the pupils pronounce with
carefuilness anzd energy.  A good test of a faithful observance of this direction, is the physical exhaustion produced;
if they do not become so weary with an eight minutes' drill
of this kind as to make it difficult to proceed further, without a change to reading or to entire rest, you may know
you are not drilling as you should.
Do not suppose, however, that you are to attend to articulation only while using the exercises specially selected for
this purpose. You can make drills in articulation, of sentences in the reading lessons, in the following manner: Select
a sentence, and direct it to be read with unusual distinctness,
so as to bring out clearly and fully every element, disregarding for the time the proper inflection and emphasis.
Concert practice may be made an efficient auxiliary in
these drills.  Designate some one of the class to pronounce
tL&gt; first word of the exercise, or to read the first sentence.
If he fails to satisfy you, pronounce it yourself, and then require the class to pronounce or read it in concert after the
model given; and, if necessary, repeat several times. Let
another pupil pronounce the next word of the exercise or
read the next sentence, the class repeating as before.
In this, as in all concert practice, the class should stand.
You will find it of advantage, also, to particularize. For
example, let the drill to-day be on the final elements, and,
64INTR OD UCTION.
while the general pronunciation is not neglected, let particular attention be paid to these; to-morrow, the initial elements may be made the subject of the lesson; at another
time, the vowel sounds. In this way, thoroughness will be
acquired, and monotony avoided. A fine exercise on the
vowel sounds is this: Choose a sentence, and pronounce
only the vowels of the syllables, but with precisely the
same emphasis, inflection, and force they would have received  had the consonants not been   dropped.   Little
difficulty will be experienced in awakening and sustaining an interest, for the exercise is amusing, and furnishes great variety, by affording the opportunity of
making selections from every style of expression and com-,position.
Finally, do not run to the extreme of imouthing. The
appearance of great effort to bring out elements with undue
force and prominence, is pedantic and thus offensive to
good taste. This is an extreme which many run into
almost unconsciously, and is, if possible, more objectionable than that of carelessness.
Thoroughness.- It is better to read one lesson well
than to pass indifferently over a dozen. The same is true
of sentences.  "Mitch, not many", should be the motto
observed. Keep your class drilling on a few well-selected
sentences, though you advance slowly through the book.
To this end, it will be well to devote the first five or ten
minutes of each recitation to. drill work, before beginning
the regular lesson.
One difficulty you will have to contend with is thie
prevalent, though mistaken notion, that the progress of
the pupil is in proportion to the number of pages and
books passed over. Reading in the Fifth Reader is considered evidence of greater ability to read than reading
in the Fourth or Third; and going through the Sixth is
synonymous with graduating in the art. To this opinion
you may have to yield to a degree; but you need not, and
you should not, compromise your own judgment, by conforming your method of teaching thereto. Keep the motto
I. R..--6.PREFACE.
TEACHERS' INSTITUTES are now held periodically in nearly every
county of the states in which Free Schools have been established;
and Normal Schools are annually increasing in number and influence. The Author's experience in such schools satisfies hlim that,
while there are many excellent works on Elocution, and numerous
valuable series of Readers, no single book has yet been presented to
the public which contains all the variety of exercises in the different
grades and styles that is necessary in presenting to teachers the subject,l How to teach Reading.
It is customary, in most Institutes, to use books fitted only for the
higher grades of our Common Schools, to illustrate the subject of
Primary, as well as advanced instruction in Reading. This is manifestly wrong-as much so as to use the Calculus to illustrate methods
of instruction in Primary Arithmetic.
In Normal Schools, it is more customary to use a series of Readers.
This is better, but more expensive, as only a small portion of each
book is needed for illustrative purposes.
It is mainly to meet this evident want of a reading book for training schools, that the present work has been prepared. The other
purposes'of the book are indicated by the following synopsis:
Part I. contains practical directioins to primlary teachers, followed
by exercises fromt the Priimler and First and Second Readers.
Part II. continues the directions, and contains a Manual of Articulation for drill purposes, and a series of reading lessons from the
Third, Fourth, and Fifth Readers.
