above given constantly in mind, and advance only rapi(lly
enough to prevent your pupils f'rom becoming discouraged.
From what has been said, it must not be inferred, however, that chere is no advantage in reading many pages.
On the contrary, it gives a readiness in calling words which
is essential to good reading, and which can be acquired in
no other way. The practice is objectionable only so far as
it leads to the substitution of quantity for quality. Encourage your pupils to read many lessons and many books outside of the recitation and the school-room.
What End is to be accomplished in Reading?
It is in place here to call particular attention to this question. We have just intimated that some regard the qua;ti'ty
read as constituting the basis of success. Others suppose
that it consists in elocution, or the ability to express audibly
to others, and in a clear and forcible manner, the words
and thoughts contained in the book. Now, it is not our
intention to lessen the importance of these things, but to
call attention to another very desirable end to be accomplished.
Pupils should be taught to remnemzber what they read, and
to express it in a connected and intelligible manner. The
relative importance of this acquisition and that of the ability
to read for the benefit of others, may be seen by comparing
what we read for our own information with what we read
for the entertainment of others. Is it not safe to say that
for every page we read aloud, we read a hundred silently?
Both attainments may be acquired, and both should demand
the attention of the teacher. Other things being equal, that,
pupil will read best who has studied his lesson so as to give
the substance of it in consecutive order, without the use of
the book.
How can this department be cultivated? In Readers,
the questions appended to each lesson are intended to assist
in this. In studying, pupils should be taught to remember
that they will be expected to answer all the questions as
well as to read the lesson. This plan, by question and answer, is a good one; but the knowledge thus obtained is
66INTtROD UCTIO-N.
likely to be fragmentary. Unity of thought and connectedness of ideas are absolutely essential to render knowledge of
practical utility..To assist in reaching this result, the following plan is suggested: Require your pupils to relate the
substance of the lesson in consecutive order. Sometimes
have a single pupil go over the whole of it, and when he
has done, call upon the class for criticisms or omissions of
important parts; at other times, call upon a pupil to begin
at the first, and when he has gone far enough, stop him,
and let another take up the subject at that point and continue it; so with the third and fourth, until all have been
called upon. If the pupils are young and timid, assist them
by an occasional question or suggestion.
Inquire for the Meaning.-Teach your pupils to inquire for the sense of the passage, and then to give it by
appropriate emphasis and inflection. The teacher ought
to be able to furnish a model of correct reading, and, while
insisting upon its being observed, should still judiciously
encourage originality in his pupils. When once a spirit of
inquiry is aroused, it begets interest, awakens thought, and
makes bold, manly readers, instead of slavish imitators.
Originality may be encouraged by the suggestions of the
teacher. For example: take the sentence, " This is a beautiful day". Read it: "This is a beautiful day". Ask if it
can be read so as to express a different meaning. One
responds, "This is a beautzjful day"; another, "This is a
beautiful day". It may be read as an exclamatory sentence,
as an interrogative one, in a tone of great amazement, in a
laughing manner; and so on, in different styles, arresting
tile attention of the class, and convincing them that reading
does not consist alone in calling words. Having once
awakened inquiry and interest, in this way, you can easily
transfer it to the sentences of the reading lesson.
How to Study a Reading Lesson.-- Teach a pupil
how to study, and you have put him at once upon the highroad to success; and yet few teachers ever give instruction
in this mo6t useful and essential part of an education.
07INSTITUTE READER.
In making their preparation, direct the pupils to first read
tlue lesson over, in order to get the story and its connections; then to return, and re-read the first paragraph more
carefully, and, if necessary, to repeat again sentence by
sentence, emphasizing the different words, until a reading is
decided upon, which seenis to express the fullest Imeaning.'I'his preparation should be made at home, where thev can
read aloud, thereby having the ear to assist the judgment in
determining the correct reading.  Never test the preparation by the number of times the pupil has read the lesson,
unless you know how t/orou,ghzly he has read it.
Marks and Pauses.-Pupils, from the beginning, ought
to be taught to recognize and name the more common
marks; and by the time they have completed the Fourth
Reader, they should possess a tolerably correct idea of
punctuaton and its use in reading. The distinction between grammatical and rhetorical pauses should next demand attention, for it is the key to the subject. The
former, indicated by various points, are essentially the
writer's, and are employed by him to convey his meaning.
It is by the latter, which usually are not indicated by marks
at all, that the meaning is expressed in reading. The old
method, therefore, of teaching to stop long enough at a
comma to count onze, at a semicolon long enough to count
two, etc., is not only an erroneous, but a forced method.
Pupils who have a clear conception of the distinction mentioned, and a correct idea of the. author's meaning, will
experience little difficulty in deciding where and how long
to pause.
Criticisms.-Objection is sometimes made to the practice of class criticism, that it encourages a spirit of faultfinding, on the part of putpils, toward one another. In
cases where such a spirit prevails, the teacher is often to
blame for it; for, by a few well-timed remarks, he may
check even a tendency in this direction, and awaken a
aesire for mnutual instruction.
When a pupil has finished a sentence or paragraph, call
68INTROD UCTION.
on members of the class individually for criticisms on the
emphasis, inflection, articulation, pronunciation, position
in standing, manner of holding the book, or any other real
fau/t; but allow no trifling. If any faults remain uncorrected, notice them yourself, and then direct the pupil to
re-read, making the corrections suggested.
An error many teachers fall into, is that of reqluiring
criticisms only on the miscalling of words. It is generally
a very marked defect to miscall, omit, or insert a word;
but errors of this kind frequently do not mar the beauty nor
injure the sense of the passage so much as a wrong inflection, a lifeless delivery, or even a repetition.
With the younger pupils, attending to too many things at
a time may distract the attention and confuse the mind.
You will, therefore, find it of advantage to devote one week
to criticisms on emphasis, another to criticisms on delivery,
and so on, until you have considered all departments.
Modulation.--This consists in that pleasing variety
which is at once both agreeable and forcible; but it is so
involved with other matters that it is difficult to treat of it
as a distinct department of reading. If the voice be well
developed and trained, and the inflection and emphasis be
properly attended to, modulation will need but little special
attention.
A close examination of most pieces of composition will
disclose the fact that there are many words and phrases
which are merely explanatory of the main ideas. Such
words and phrases, though they be not set off by the usual
parenthesis marks, are, nevertheless, parenthetical, and
should be read at a more rapid rate, and in a little lower tone
of voi;:e, than the other parts. Finding out the parenthetical portions should occupy a large share of the pupil's attention iwhile studying his lesson; and an observance of them
in reading will add materially to the beauty of the modulation, beside giving additional force to the meaning.
Manner of Reading Poetry.-The melody of verse
requires two kinds of pauses, peculiar to itself, in addition0INSTITUTE READER.
to the grammatical pauses: a slight one at the end of the
line, and the cxsural, at or neir the middle. W*\hen the
grammatical and caesural pauses coincide, but little difficulty
is experienced in reading verse.
Blank verse ought also to be read so as to make every
line distinct to the ear, else it differs in no way from prose,
and the poet has composed in numbers to no purpose.
When there is no pause in the meaning, at the end of
the line, it ought not to be marked by such a tone or inflection as is needed at the close of a sentence; but, without
fall or elevation, it should be denoted only by so slight a
suspension of sound as will distinguish one from  another
without injuring the meaning. A like suspension of the
sound should mark the cxesural pause.
To read poetry properly, one must have a correct idea
of the author's meaning, a lively appreciation of the sentiment, and an ear for melody; but, above all, he must avoid
the sing-song tone so commonly used.
Select Readings.-These consist of short selections
for reading, made by the pupils themselves from the Readers or from other sources, and are useful in awakening
enthusiasm, without which but little can be accomplished
in teaching.
The regular time allotted to reading may frequently be
set apart for this purpose, or an occasional half-day can not
be employed to greater adv?:ltage by the school.
If there should be a hes tancy about volunteering on the
part of those who most n,i d the drill, it would be well for
you to make appointment,. It will, perhaps, be necessary
also for you to make sele tions for the younger pupils and
for the backward ones: for it frequently occurs that childreIl
loss much time by indecision; and even when they have
made selections, they may have so little confidence in their
own judgmnent as to cause them to fail in the reading, T-he
aim of the teacher should be, not to relieve the pupil from
the exercise of judgment, but rather to encourage him in
it by judicious assistance.'10INTROD UCTION.
DECLAMATION.
Declamation beside being in every way, a valuable auxiliary to reading, serves the double purpose, also, of relieving the monotony of the regular school exercises, and imparting to the pupils confidence and self-possession.  Many
a man who now possesses the power of thirnking oan his feel
before an audience, owes it to the self-possession acquired
by declaiming in the school-room. Perhaps an injudicious
use of declamation has been injurious to some schools; but:he abuse, and not the use, is on that account to be condemned.
No doubt, a difficulty which teachers experience, is an
almost universal prejudice, on the part of pupils, against
declaiming. How to remove this prejudice, and get pupils
interested in the exercise, is the important matter. This
may be done by having a true conception of the end to be
accomplished, and by beginning right. Let the first exercises of this character be in the reading-class. Commence
with a single sentence or paragraph; let the class repeat it
in concert, in the most natural manner possible, making the
appropriate gestures, if any; afterward require the pupils to
repeat it separately. When you have succeeded, by this
means, in removing the novelty, and consequently the emharrasment, usually attached to declaiming, you can set
apart an occasional half-day, as was suggested with reference to select readings, and conduct the exercises according
to the customary method.
Selection.-Success in declamation depends, in a very
great degree, upon a proper selection; and boys and girls
of immature judgment, if left to themselves, are almost sure
to select pieces beyond their comprehension.  Place before
a boy a dramatic and a simple narrative piece of composition, from which to make a choice, and, in a majority of
cases, he will take the former. This does not appear so
strange, however, when we remember that he has, perhaps,
heard the same recited by a professional reader, or some
71INSTITUI'E READER.
one else, and has conceived the idea of imitating it. Generally the descriptive and narrative styles will be most
appropriate; for in these, the expression is simpler and
more easily comprehended, and without the comprehension,
no one can'succeed in rendering the sense by appropriate
emphasis, inflection, and delivery.
Delivery.-Be not ambitious to have your pupils shozo
off, but rather desire for them the accomplishments of naturalness and gracefulness.  Do not mistake sound for sense,
cant and rage for the earnestness of nature; for those who
do "are capable of nothing but inexplicable dumb-show and
noise".  Many who might acquit themselves creditably in
plain recitation, spoil the effect by trying to be eloqueznt. In
declamation as in reading,
"He who in earnest studies o'er his part,
Will find true nature cling about his heart."
The delivery should be deliberate. With the eyes of tlhe
entire school upon him, the declaimer is apt to become
excited by the novelty of the situation, and is inclined
almost irresistibly to get through, and return to hIis seat
as soon as possible. To prevent the indistinct utterance
and imperfect observance of pauses into which he is so
likely to fall, aid him, by some means, to forget himself,
and -to become interested in what he has to say.  Criticise
the tone, and endeavor to have it not only pure, but
adapted to the style of composition also.
Gesture.-Do not attempt too much in gesture, but
what you do teach, teach thoroughly.  The great object to
be aimed at is gracefulness. All the movements of the beginner will be stiff and awkward, from the bow at the beginning to the bow at the close: practice only can overcome
these defects.  You will have but little success with individuals for a while; and as self-possession is the key to a
graceful and easy manner, you can not more easily cultivate
this quality than by class drills in movements.
The teacher standing in front of the class, all speak the
72INTROD UCTTON.
words, around, beneath, on hizh; and on pronouncing each
word, make the appropriate gesture. Also use the hand and
arm, without pronouncing words: the teacher counts, and
the class execute the movements together.  First, move the
hand, the wrist bending; next, the forearm, bending it at the
elbow; then move the whole arm at the shoulder. The art
of graceful gesticulation lies in keeping the muscles moderately relaxed.  When the gesture is completed, do not
allow the hand to faS to the side, as though it were lifeless;
neither bring it down stiffly; but let it return to its place in
a graceful manner.
The manner of bringing up the hand is significant.
Generally the hand should be raised above the place where
it is intended to stop, and brought down to it with more or
less energy, according to the sentiment. It should reach
the emphatic rest precisely on the emphatic word.
As a rule, oratorical gestures should be executed in easy,
graceful curves; invective, in straight lines and angles.
The movements of the feet, as well as those of the
hands, must be looked after. While too much stepping in
declamation is objectionable, as giving the appearance of
rant, too little, on the other- hand, conveys the impression
of stiffness.
The following will afford sufficient variety for drill purposes: Standing with the heels together, the toes turned
outward, step obliquely to the front, with the right foot in
the direction the toe points, and bring the left foot to the
right, the two occupying the same relative position as before the movement. In returning, each foot passes through
the same movement as in advancing, only the order is
reversed. Go through the same movements, beginning with
the left foot.
